\begin_layout Section
Context and description of maize value chains in Uganda
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maize is one of the most widely cultivated staple crops in Uganda,
 serving both as a vital food security crop and a key source of income for farmers.
 Recognizing its importance,
 the government has prioritized maize production as part of its agricultural strategy to support household livelihoods and strengthen national food security.
 Maize accounts for approximately 30% of the total cropped land in Uganda,
 making it the most extensively grown crop,
 followed by beans at 15% (Uganda Annual Agricultural Survey,
 2018).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A typical maize value chain in Uganda involves a network of interconnected actors.
 At the upstream level,
 agro-input dealers supply essential inputs such as improved seeds and fertilizers to smallholder farmers.
